Strategies and tools
______________________________________
Sequence Alignment Tools and Strategies
______________________________________

*
BLAST & Align tools in databases
https://blast.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/Blast.cgi
https://www.uniprot.org/align
For comparing nucleotide or protein sequences to sequence databases.
Distinguishing feature: High speed and sensitivity for finding local alignments.
Psi-BLAST
For detecting distant relationships between protein sequences.
Distinguishing feature: Iterative search using position-specific scoring matrices.
*
Clustal Omega
https://www.ebi.ac.uk/jdispatcher/msa/clustalo
For multiple sequence alignment of protein and nucleotide sequences.
Distinguishing feature: High accuracy and scalability for large datasets.
*
MAFFT (Multiple Alignment using Fast Fourier Transform)
https://www.ebi.ac.uk/jdispatcher/msa/mafft
For large-scale multiple sequence alignment.
Distinguishing feature: Fast and accurate, especially for sequences with high similarity.
*
T-Coffee
https://tcoffee.crg.eu/
When to use: For accurate multiple sequence alignment.
Distinguishing feature: Combines results from several alignment methods to improve accuracy.
*
MUSCLE
https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/15034147/
https://www.drive5.com/muscle/ 
For multiple sequence alignment.
Distinguishing feature: High accuracy and speed, suitable for medium to large datasets.
*
BWA (Burrows-Wheeler Aligner)
https://bio-bwa.sourceforge.net/
For mapping low-divergent sequences against a large reference genome.
Distinguishing feature: Fast and memory-efficient, suitable for short reads.
*
Bowtie
https://bowtie-bio.sourceforge.net/index.shtml
For aligning short DNA sequences to the reference genome.
Distinguishing feature: Ultra-fast and memory-efficient for short read alignment.
Bowtie2
For aligning long DNA sequences.
Distinguishing feature: Improved accuracy and speed over Bowtie for long reads.
GMAP (Genomic Mapping and Alignment Program)

*
HISAT2
https://daehwankimlab.github.io/hisat2/
For alignment of both DNA and RNA sequences.
Distinguishing feature: Fast and sensitive alignment, supports large genomes.
*
STAR (Spliced Transcripts Alignment to a Reference)
https://hbctraining.github.io/Intro-to-rnaseq-hpc-O2/lessons/03_alignment.html 
For aligning RNA-Seq reads.
Distinguishing feature: Handles spliced reads and provides fast and accurate results.
*
TopHat
https://academic.oup.com/bioinformatics/article/25/9/1105/203994
Center for Computational Biology at Johns Hopkins University
https://tophat.cbcb.umd.edu/
For discovering splice junctions in RNA-Seq data.
Distinguishing feature: Builds on Bowtie, specifically for RNA-Seq data analysis.
*
Smith-Waterman Algorithm
https://ir.lib.uth.gr/xmlui/bitstream/handle/11615/48888/16488.pdf?sequence=1&isAllowed=y
https://cs.stanford.edu/people/eroberts/courses/soco/projects/computers-and-the-hgp/smith_waterman.html
When to use: For local sequence alignment.
Distinguishing feature: Provides optimal local alignment, but computationally intensive.
*
EMBOSS Water
https://www.bioinformatics.nl/cgi-bin/emboss/help/water
For local sequence alignment using the Smith-Waterman algorithm.
Distinguishing feature: Part of the EMBOSS suite, suitable for detailed pairwise alignment.
*
Needleman-Wunsch Algorithm
https://vlab.amrita.edu/?sub=3&brch=274&sim=1431&cnt=1
For global sequence alignment.
Distinguishing feature: Provides optimal global alignment for entire sequences.
*
Mummer
For aligning large DNA sequences, such as whole genomes.
Distinguishing feature: Highly efficient for large-scale sequence alignment.
*
Kalign
For multiple sequence alignment of protein and nucleotide sequences.
Distinguishing feature: Very fast, suitable for aligning large datasets.
*
ProbCons
For multiple sequence alignment of proteins.
Distinguishing feature: High accuracy, probabilistic consistency-based alignment.
*
Dialign
For segment-based multiple sequence alignment.
Distinguishing feature: Aligns segments rather than individual residues, useful for sequences with rearrangements.


SSAHA (Sequence Search and Alignment by Hashing Algorithm)
For fast database searches.
Distinguishing feature: Uses hashing for rapid sequence alignment.


Exonerate
For aligning DNA and protein sequences.
Distinguishing feature: Flexible alignment strategies, suitable for various sequence types.

CLUSTALW
For multiple sequence alignment.
Distinguishing feature: Widely used, balances speed and accuracy.

MAQ (Mapping and Assembly with Quality)
For mapping short reads and SNP calling.
Distinguishing feature: Combines alignment with variant calling, suitable for small genomes.

SOAP2
For aligning short reads to a reference genome.
Distinguishing feature: High speed and efficiency, especially for large-scale projects.


Paywall or License Required Sequence Alignment Tools and Strategies

Novoalign
For aligning short reads to a reference genome.
Distinguishing feature: High sensitivity and specificity, handles base calling errors.

Geneious Alignment
For easy-to-use sequence alignment.
Distinguishing feature: Integrated in a user-friendly bioinformatics suite.
